>From: gregory_smith@ccmail.gsfc.nasa.gov (Gregory A. Smith)
>Subject: FoxPro Vs. Client-Server RBDMS
>Date: 8 Sep 1994 15:23:56 GMT

>Can anyone tell if there are any objective metrics for when to move from
>Xbase File-Server Architecture (such as FoxPro) to a Client-Server RDBMS
>Architecture (such as Sybase-Powerbuilder)?

>For instance, is there a threshold in number of records, megabytes of
>data or number of simultaneous users at which FoxPro should be ruled
>out as a development tool.

It all depends on what you do with it.  Foxpro is extremely fast in terms of 
transaction processing - adding a record or changing a record.  Foxpro stinks 
on the other hand if you are searching through large amounts of data - if your 
users are looking through lists of invoices, or some such.  I've run code that 
bangs over 1G of files, and it runs OK.  I wouldn't buy an HP to save 
myself 3 hours of run time if I only run the thing once a week.  The benefits 
of going to C-S are numerous, but as with any tool it works well on SOME tasks.
If you've looked at PB you'll probably conclude that it is a much more of a 
development tool than Foxpro - it is designed to handle large scale projects, 
with inheritance, and other such.  I've been using a combination of Foxpro and 
PB to talk to a Watcom database sitting on a Novell server, and there are 
tasks I would not want to touch with PB, and there are tasks that Foxpro is 
just not as well suited for...  As to the user count this is more of a network 
throughput (and locking) issue - even if your application reads very little 
data, 2000 users are going to nail your network in a blink.  If you are 
starting any new medium to large scale projects (120h+ in my book), I'd start 
in PB and look for places where Foxpro applies better.

>If anyone has any objective metrics, benchmarks, or statistics supporting
>such a threshold, please email them to me at:

You can do a simple calculation: in a query, Foxpro copies across all data 
needed to perform comparisons, etc.  Assume a LOCATE:

               FOXPRO                     CS
Worst Case =   FieldSize * RecCount       SQL Select + results cursor
Average Case = FieldSize * RecCount / 2   constant (as above)
Best Case =    FieldSize                  constant (as above)

Look at your data, and see what data you are bringing across...  Even if you 
use seeks, the index must be essentially copied across.  If your indexes are 
big, the same calculation applies.  The above assumes the same server on both 
ends, ie. the actual search taking about the same amount of time.  This is 
generally not true, as most SQL backends organize data to make queries very 
fast, unlike Foxpro.

