>Has anyone actually done transaction processing in their FoxPro application?
>I would love to hear some case testimonies.

If you mean a transaction as an operation that is not a query, I haven't seen 
too many applications that do NO transaction processing...  If you mean a 
transacation as an OS feature with a guaranteed rollback and database 
integrity, you CANNOT - not in Foxpro  (don't count Novell stuff - that it 
using Novell features, not Foxpro's).

>I want to write an application that can have a duplicate copy at another
>site and through the magic (read... "my months of toil and headaches") of
>software be able to "cross update" the sites so each would have the
>changes/additions/deleteions of the other site. Any insights to this?

Depending on your application, maintain a date field of LastChange.  Whenever 
you write to it, update LastChange.  Every week (or whatever) send out all 
records with LastChange in the date range, and reset them.  This assumes NO 
possibility of both sites modifyng a single record (because then you are 
really fudged).

