I would think a reasonable indicator for when to move from Fox Pro to
a client-server database would be the needs of the database. Fox Pro will
certainly handle a database of any practical size, and probably, with the
right PCs and network equipment, most any number of users.

HOWEVER, if your database requires (a) more internal _enforced_ integrity
due to complexity, (b) a large number of clients with a limited amount
of network bandwidth [say 20-30 users on an Ethernet network], (c) and
the sophistication afforded by transaction commits and rollbacks, on-line
backups, etc., then it is time to move it to a C/S setup.

To make a long story short, my company does FoxPro for big things, and we
also do C/S for big things - we just let the application decide for us
which way we do it. Rules of thumb only work when everyone has the same
thumb. ---Chris

